\description{
Groups the dead-reckoning and track-correction knobs of \code{\link{reconstructTrack}} into a
single object: how the animal's swimming speed is set, the biological speed cap, and how the drifting
reckoned path is reconciled with verified positions.
}
\details{
Dead reckoning integrates a \emph{speed} and a \emph{heading} forward in time to reconstruct a movement path (see
the "Dead reckoning in brief" section of \code{\link{reconstructTrack}}). Heading is produced upstream by
\code{\link{processTagData}}; this control object governs the two remaining ingredients - the \strong{speed}
used at each step, and the \strong{Verified Position Correction (VPC)} that ties the path back to known fixes.
\subsection{Choosing a speed method}{

Because the reckoning multiplies speed by heading, the \emph{shape} of the track is set by heading while its
\emph{scale} is set by speed. The options trade off honesty against realism:
\itemize{
\item \code{"constant"} (default) - a single nominal speed (\code{constant.speed}). The safest choice: it makes
no unsupported claim about moment-to-moment speed, so the track is shape-faithful but only nominally
scaled. Between-fix VPC still rescales each segment to the true fix-to-fix distance.
\item \code{"vedba"} - speed from a linear model \verb{speed = intercept + slope x VeDBA}, where VeDBA
(Vectorial Dynamic Body Acceleration) is the rotation-invariant activity metric computed by
\code{\link{processTagData}}. Dynamic acceleration scales with locomotor effort, so VeDBA is a strong
proxy for through-water speed (Bidder et al. 2012; Gunner et al. 2021). Supply the model via
\code{vedba.model}, or leave it \code{NULL} to auto-calibrate from the deployment's own GPS fixes (see below).
\item \code{"paddle"} - speed from a \code{paddle_speed} column (a mechanical paddle-wheel rotation count).
\item \code{"depth_rate"} - horizontal speed inferred from vertical velocity and the dive geometry
(\code{horizontal = vertical_velocity / tan(pitch)}). This is reliable ONLY on steep glides: near
horizontal, \code{1 / tan(pitch)} explodes and a small pitch error yields a wildly wrong speed, so samples
shallower than \code{depth.rate.min.pitch} are dropped and back-filled with \code{constant.speed}
(Wensveen et al. 2015). Hence it is not the default.
}
}

\subsection{VeDBA auto-calibration (\code{vedba.model = NULL})}{

When no model is supplied, \code{reconstructTrack} fits \verb{speed = intercept + slope x VeDBA} from the
deployment itself: for every pair of consecutive position fixes it forms the straight-line
(great-circle) speed and the mean VeDBA over that interval, keeps only intervals during which the animal
travelled in a near-straight line (so straight-line distance approximates the true path length), and
regresses speed on VeDBA (Gunner et al. 2021). Sparse or tortuous fix sets rarely yield enough clean
intervals; when the calibration is under-determined or non-physical (slope <= 0) the method \strong{falls back
to \code{constant.speed}} and records this in the processing log and metadata. For a definitive calibration,
fit the model externally against high-rate GPS and pass it via \code{vedba.model}.
}

\subsection{Rest gating (\code{rest.quantile})}{

Reckoning drift accumulates whenever a non-zero speed is integrated, including while the animal is
resting. Setting \code{rest.quantile} holds the speed at zero whenever VeDBA falls in its lowest quantile
(e.g. \code{0.10} = the least-active 10\% of samples), preventing spurious wandering during inactivity; Gunner
et al. (2021) found such activity-gating reduced net reconstruction error. Requires a \code{vedba} column;
\code{NULL} (default) disables it.
}
